image.caption:
🖼️ Mishiikenh Kwe (Autumn Smith). “Grandmothers”. 2022.  Acrylic paint on stretched canvas.  30" x 36" inches. Available, contact the artist @mishiikenhkwe for any purchase inquires. 
.
.
📷🎯@mishiikenhkwe 
.
.
🍁Mishiikenh Kwe (Autumn Smith) is a 24 year old self-taught Ojibway-Odawa artist from Magnetawan First Nation.
.
.
🎨 Born in 1997 in Parry Sound, Ontario, Autumn has always had an interest in art inspired by her family, her community, their stories and the land around her. She began painting in 2016 while in college.
.
.
🎓 She studied to be a Child and Youth Worker (Technicienne en education spécialisée) at Collège Boréal in Sudbury, but decided after graduation in 2018 to return home to her community and to pursue art full-time.
.
.
🖌️ Since then Autumn has used her time to paint, learn her language and spend time on the land with her 1 year old son Jiibik.
.
.
🏙️ In 2019 she contributed a mural to the Sault Ste. Marie Downtown Mural Project.
.
.

image.alt_text: Photo by Brenna Quinlan in Noongar Boodjar. May be an illustration of text that says 'Prioritize anti-oppression training Acknowledge the history + current reality of the land Acknowledge rights of Indigenous peopies BLM We are all friends O interpreters, as Have sign language needed AND SUSTAINABILITY Designate safe IN GENERAL Use inclusive WWWWW Spaces language Build rich, sumbiotic relationships with BIPOC how ach other. treat BASED ON THE REQUESTS FROM THE PEOPLE OF cOLOUR CAUCUS AT THE NORTH AMERICAN PERmAcULTURE CONVERCENCE 2014 @brenna_uinlar'.
image.caption:
Permaculture changed the course of my life. It is my friend, my philosophy, my moral compass and my lunch. I love and believe in this movement and in all the good it has achieved, which is why I'm so keen to make it even better.

Not everyone feels like permaculture is 'their' movement. Not everyone feels it acknowledges them, or speaks to their needs. But projects including @liberationpermaculture, @perma.queer and @global.permayouth are out to turn this around.

If you'd like to dive deeper into the ideas in this illustration, I'd highly recommend downloading issue #98 of @permaculturedesignmagazine on Decolonising Permaculture. It's packed with important and exciting ways to help move this global movement forward on issues of race, equality and social justice.

"We request that as we reconnect with the land through the practice of permaculture, the permaculture community actively seeks out and publicly acknowledges both the history and current reality of the land as it relates to struggles against colonisation, conquest and oppression" - the People of Colour Caucus at the NAPC.

This stuff is important, not just for permies but for everyone working to make a difference wherever they are.

Let us know in the comments what resources you'd recommend to break down barriers and make the movement stronger.

#artasactivism #brennaquinlan #permacultureillustrator

image.caption: Child protection isn't sorry for stealing our children and they aren't sorry for the pain and suffering inflicted upon our Stolen Generation victim/survivors. The system doesn't need anymore tokenistic add ons, it simply needs to be abolished. The system is illegal and should not be touching our children and our families. Period.  #ourkidsbelongwithfamily #abolishchildprotection #childprotection #childstealers #illegal #australia #firstnations #handsoffourkids #stolengeneration #apology #gammindawgs #tokenism #crisis

image.alt_text: Photo shared by jakeyduke on January 25, 2022 tagging @danmaher__, @clothingthegaps, and @refuse_to_lose_podcast. May be an image of one or more people, people standing and outdoors.
image.caption:
Personally, Invasion Day is a very conflicting and confusing time. It brings about two prominent but ultimately contrasting emotions; gratitude and guilt. I am grateful for my privilege. Grateful that, for the most part, I have not had to experience the pain, loss, dispossession,
discrimination and degradation so many of my black brothers and sisters have experienced. I wasn’t born in a tent like my Aunties and uncles were; I wasn’t beaten by cops like some of my mates were, I wasn’t robbed of basic education or clean water like the children I’ve met in the Northern Territory. 

Because my mother was white and came from a well off family, I was spared these injustices. But when I stand on Gadigal land today and hear the stories of those who have lost family members to deaths in custody, or those who have lost loved ones because of Intergenerational trauma and a system not set up to support them, I feel a great sense of guilt about how lucky I have been. 

This week the Australian Government ‘Freed the Flag’. A momentous occasion, but still only one of the first steps in a long battle. What really matters is statistics like the following …

Aboriginal men are 40% more likely to commit suicide.

An Aboriginal person is unlikely to live long enough to claim their superannuation.

The mortality rate for Aboriginal women during childbirth is 3-5 times higher. 

Freeing the flag, changing the date or the anthem are all important. But more than anything, they are battering rams for knocking down the barriers of inequality. The more people learn about the racist and colonial undertones behind these so called ‘Aussie traditions’, the more they realise how much of that injustice and disadvantage is still prominent today and the very real consequences it has on peoples lives. Yes, it’s a very complicated and difficult issue … but it has to start somewhere. So we don’t just march for a change of date, we march for equality and for those in power to do more everyday to help First Nations Australians. Thanks to all of those who are a part of the solution 🖤💛❤️ #changethedate #blacklivesmatter #invasionday  #firstnations #notthedatetocelebrate #alwayswasalwayswillbe
